<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-386-616  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 386 616.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Macworld  June 1990 v7 n6 p97(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Programming for the rest of us. (Macintosh programming)(State ofthe Mac) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Webster, Bruce F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Apple Macintosh is one of the most difficult computers toprogram.andP;  Few commercially-available programming languages for theMac are good choices for the novice user because Mac programmingrequires large amounts of code for the user interface, and it hasa steep learning curve.andP;  Its toolbox interface is Pascal-oriented,making programming in other languages even more difficult.andO;Symantec Corp's Think C and Think Pascal compilers both provideobject-oriented extensions and a Mac class library to simplifyroutine programming tasks.andP;  HyperCard, Apple's first attempt atcreating a true end-user programming tool, has not revolutionizedMac software because it deviates from the standard Mac interface.andO;Object oriented programming environments are widely touted as apanacea for programming difficulties.andP;  Apple already has a goodclass library in its MacApp, but Apple management failed tosupport its development or promote its use until early 1988.andP;  Notruly ideal solution for Mac programming yet exists; a superiorhybrid environment would let users build a Mac interface, link theelements and define behavior with a powerful scripting language.andO;Pre-written software modules would be usable in multipleapplications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (programming).andO;Topic:     Program Development TechniquesProgramming LanguagesObject-Oriented Programming.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>